'''Artur Asilbekovich Beterbiev''' ({{lang-ru|Артур Асильбекович Бетербиев}}; born 21 January 1985) is a Russian [[professional boxer]] who has held the [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] [[light-heavyweight]] title since 2017. As of June 2018, he is ranked as the world's seventh best active light-heavyweight by ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'' magazine, and eighth by the [[Transnational Boxing Rankings Board]] and [[BoxRec]].

As an [[amateur boxing|amateur]], Beterbiev won a silver medal at the [[2007 World Amateur Boxing Championships|2007 World Championships]], gold at the [[2009 World Amateur Boxing Championships|2009 World Championships]], as well as gold at the [[2006 European Amateur Boxing Championships|2006]] and [[2010 European Amateur Boxing Championships|2010 European Championships]], all in the light-heavyweight division. He also reached the quarter-finals of the [[heavyweight]] bracket at the [[2012 Olympics]].

Beterbiev is particularly known for his exceptional punching power, having scored all of his professional wins by [[knockout]] or [[technical knockout|stoppage]].<ref>Idec, Keith (23 December 2016). [http://www.boxingscene.com/beterbiev-stops-prieto-first-round-keep-ko-streak-intact--112049 "Beterbiev Stops Prieto in First Round to Keep KO Streak Intact"]. BoxingScene. Retrieved 24 December 2016.</ref>

==Amateur career==
Beterbiev competed as a light-heavyweight and [[heavyweight]] in his [[amateur boxing|amateur]] career.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Artur Beterbiyev Bio, Stats, and Results|url = https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/be/artur-beterbiyev-1.html|website = Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate = 2015-09-24}}</ref> He won the [[2006 European Amateur Boxing Championships]] beating [[Kenneth Egan]] and [[Ismail Sillakh]] among others. He beat [[Egor Mekhontsev]] but lost to two-time world champion [[Evgeny Makarenko]] in 2006.{{Clarify|reason = At which competition?|date=September 2015}} In 2007 he beat future unified light-heavyweight champion [[Sergey Kovalev (boxer)|Sergey Kovalev]] in the semi-finals, and eventually beat [[Evgeny Makarenko]] in finals to qualify for the World Championships. In the finals of the World Championships he faced the little-known [[Abbos Atoev]] but lost in an upset.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aiba.org/documents/site1/wch_chicago/C74E49.pdf |title=AIBA World Boxing Championships Chicago 2007 Results |date= |accessdate=24 September 2015 |website= |publisher=AIBA |last= |first= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613104556/http://aiba.org/documents/site1/wch_chicago/C74E49.pdf |archivedate=June 13, 2010 }}</ref>

At the [[2008 Summer Olympics|Olympics 2008]] he beat [[Kennedy Katende]] 15:3 then fell controversially to local boxer [[Zhang Xiaoping]] who went on to win the gold medal.

In Milan he beat young Cuban [[Jose Larduet]] and Uzbek [[Elshod Rasulov]] for the 2009 world championship title.

At the [[2011 World Amateur Boxing Championships|2011 World Championships]] he lost to eventual winner [[Oleksandr Usyk]] by 13–17. At the [[2012 Olympics]] he edged out Michael Hunter but lost again by 13–17 to Usyk. Both of these were in the heavyweight division.

==Professional career==
===Early career===
Beterbiev moved to [[Montreal]] to pursue a professional career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.groupeyvonmichel.ca/eng/boxers/artur_beterbiev-eng.html|title=Artur Beterbiev - GYM|first=Mondial|last=Web|website=www.groupeyvonmichel.ca}}</ref> He won his professional debut via a second-round [[technical knockout|TKO]] over Christian Cruz at the [[Bell Centre]] on July 8, 2013. Beterbiev fought on the undercard of [[Jean Pascal vs. Lucian Bute]], beating Gabriel Lecrosnier by TKO on the fourth round.

===North American champion===
====Beterbiev vs. Cloud====
After winning his first five professional bouts, Beterbiev would face off against former [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] [[light-heavyweight]] champion [[Tavoris Cloud]] for the vacant [[North American Boxing Association|NABA]] title on September 27, 2014. After a tentative opening minute from both fighters, Beterbiev opened up and began landing powerful shots that visibly rocked Cloud. In the final minute, the Russian would drop his opponent three times via combinations. Before this fight, Cloud had never been dropped in his professional career.  Beterbiev would close the show in round two, landing multiple hard shots to the head that knocked Cloud out, giving Beterbiev his first title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/dan-rafael/post/_/id/10524/beterbiev-dominates-stops-cloud|title=Beterbiev dominates, stops Cloud|publisher=}}</ref>

====Beterbiev vs. Page, Campillo====
On December 2014, Beterbiev stopped light heavyweight prospect Jeff Page Jr. in two rounds, winning the vacant IBF North American and [[North American Boxing Organization|NABO]] light-heavyweight titles. However, Beterbiev was dropped for the first time in a professional fight in the first stanza of the fight. "I felt a bit sleepy before the fight. I think I just lost my concentration for a fraction of a second," Beterbiev said of the knockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/12/19/7425761/artur-beterbiev-gets-off-canvas-stops-jeff-page-in-round-two|title=Beterbiev dropped, but stops Page in two|publisher=}}</ref> Afterwards, Beterbiev would face off against another former IBF world champion, [[Gabriel Campillo]], with his North American title at stake. Both men began cautiously until Beterbiev dropped Campillo late in the first round. The Russian slowly wore down his foe with multiple straight rights to the body. Finally in the fourth, Beterbiev would land a straight/uppercut hybrid that would hit Campillo square on the chin, and followed it up with a perfunctory left hook before walking to his corner while his opponent slid to the canvas, barely conscious.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2015/4/4/8345149/pbc-on-cbs-results-artur-beterbiev-smashes-gabriel-campillo-in-four|title=Beterbiev smashes Campillo in four|publisher=}}</ref> The PSI detector in his gloves stated that the first punch landed with 973 [[pounds per square inch]]{{cn|date=November 2017}}.

====Subsequent defenses====
Beterbiev improved his record to 9-0 against Alexander Johnson on June 12, 2015 at the UIC Pavilion in [[Chicago]]. Beterbiev knocked Johnson down twice in the fifth and a third time in the seventh before finishing him at 1:38 of the round, clobbering him with a left hook and finishing him off with a overhand right that put Johnson through the ropes down and out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierboxingchampions.com/beterbiev-vs-johnson|title=Beterbiev vs Johnson Results & Highlights - Jun 12, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> With the win, Beterbiev added the vacant [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] International light-heavyweight title to his other four minor titles.

On June 2016, Beterbiev defeated [[Ezequiel Maderna]] by round 4 TKO, dropping him four times along the way.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierboxingchampions.com/news/beterbiev-turns-power-gain-fourth-round-tko-maderna|title=Beterbiev turns up the power to gain fourth-round TKO of Maderna|publisher=}}</ref> Beterbiev's eleventh professional win came against Isidro Prieto, whom he knocked out after a flurry of punches at the end of the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2016/12/24/14075128/artur-beterbiev-destroys-isidro-prieto-in-one|title=Beterbiev crushes Prieto in one|publisher=}}</ref> Beterbiev had several title eliminators and world title shots fall through, including bouts against [[Sullivan Barrera]], [[Igor Mikhalkin]], and [[Sergey Kovalev (boxer)|Sergey Kovalev]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/beterbiev-barrera-alvarez-chilemba-double-november--96114|title=Beterbiev-Barrera, Alvarez-Chilemba Double in November?|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/13935493/shoulder-injury-knocks-artur-beterbiev-world-title-elimination-fight|title=Beterbiev (shoulder) out of world title eliminator|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/dan-rafael/post/_/id/13647/no-kovalev-beterbiev-no-surprise|title=No Kovalev-Beterbiev? No surprise|publisher=}}</ref> He also faced long periods of inactivity in a promotional dispute against Yvon Michel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2017/5/10/15614166/beterbiev-attempts-to-cut-ties-with-promoter-yvon-michel|title=Beterbiev seeks split from promoter Yvon Michel|publisher=}}</ref>

===Beterbiev vs. Kölling===
On July 2017, Beterbiev had yet another world title eliminator fall through. He was scheduled to face [[Enrico Kölling]], with the winner becoming the [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]]'s mandatory challenger to unified world champion [[Andre Ward]], but the fight was never finalized amidst Beterbiev's contract dispute.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2017/7/19/15997836/artur-beterbiev-enrico-koelling-canceled|title=Beterbiev’s title eliminator with Koelling canceled|publisher=}}</ref> A [[purse bid]] was later won by [[Top Rank]], with the American promotion planning to broadcast the fight on [[ESPN]], as part of a show including [[Jessie Magdaleno]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/20155415/top-rank-wins-purse-bid-artur-beterbiev-enrico-koelling-world-title-eliminator|title=Top Rank wins purse bid to Beterbiev-Koelling|publisher=}}</ref> The show was later announced to be taking place on November 11 at the [[Save Mart Arena]] in [[Fresno]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2017/9/14/16309754/jessie-magdaleno-artur-beterbiev-set-for-november-11th-espn-show|title=Magdaleno, Beterbiev set for 11/11 ESPN show|publisher=}}</ref> Magdaleno would later drop out with an injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2017/10/8/16444160/jessie-magdaleno-injured-out-of-november-11-fight|title=Jessie Magdaleno injured, out of November 11 fight|publisher=}}</ref>

Andre Ward officially announced his retirement on September, therefore the IBF title became vacant. The IBF later announced that the fight between Beterbiev and Kölling would be for the now-vacant world title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/20850651/artur-beterbiev-enrico-koelling-elimination-bout-upgraded-fight-vacant-world-title|title=Beterbiev-Koelling upgraded to world title fight|publisher=}}</ref> Beterbiev dominated Kölling in a dull fight, walking him down while Kölling refused to engage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.badlefthook.com/2017/11/12/16639142/top-rank-on-espn-results-jose-ramirez-artur-beterbiev-win-in-fresno|title=Top Rank on ESPN results: Jose Ramirez, Artur Beterbiev win in Fresno|publisher=}}</ref> Beterbiev finally scored a knockdown in round 12, as Kölling went down on one knee and received a count. When the fight resumed, Beterbiev dropped Kölling again and the referee waved the fight off. Beterbiev landed 322 of 1,111 punches (29 percent) while Kölling landed 64 of 252 blows (25 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/21380616/artur-beterbiev-stops-enrico-koelling-wins-vacant-light-heavyweight-title|title=Beterbiev stops Koelling, wins vacant light heavyweight title|publisher=}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Beterbiev was born in [[Khasavyurt]], [[Dagestan]], and is of [[Chechen people|Chechen]] descent. He currently resides in his adopted hometown of [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]. Beterbiev is a [[Muslim]], and married with three children; a son and two daughters. He is promoted by Groupe Yvon Michel (GYM) and advised by [[Al Haymon]], following his move to Canada in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/former-boxing-world-champion-beterbiev-signs-promoter-michel-222141837.html|title=Former boxing world champion Beterbiev signs on with promoter Michel|publisher=Yahoo News}}</ref>

