{{Infobox Prime Minister | name = Ide Anak Agung Gde Agung | image = COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM De minister-president van Oost-Indonesië Ide Anak Agung Gde Agung na afloop van de installatie van de Minahasa-raad op Celebes TMnr 60048844.jpg | caption = Ide Anak Agung Gde Agung (center) in [[North Sulawesi]] | order = 3rd Prime Minister of the [[State of East Indonesia]] | term_start = 15 December 1947 | term_end = 27 December 1949 | president = [[Tjokorda Gde Raka Soekawati]] | predecessor = Warouw | successor = [[J.E. Tatengkeng]] | order2 = Interior Minister of the [[United States of Indonesia]] | term_start2 = 20 December 1949 | term_end2 = 6 September 1950 | president2 = [[Sukarno]] | predecessor2 = [[Wongsonegoro]] | successor2 = [[Assaat]] | order3 = Foreign Minister of [[Indonesia]] | term_start3 = 12 August 1955 | term_end3 = 24 March 1956 | president3 = [[Sukarno]] | predecessor3 = [[Soenario]] | successor3 = [[Roeslan Abdulgani]] | order4 = 6th Indonesian [[Ambassador]] to [[Austria]] | predecessor4 = Laili Roesad | successor4 = Abdullah Kamil | term_start4 = 1970 | term_end4 = 1974 | birth_date = {{Birth date|1921|7|21|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Gianyar]], [[Bali]], [[Dutch East Indies]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1999|4|22|1921|7|21|df=yes}} | death_place = | party = | spouse = | profession = | religion = [[Hinduism]] | signature = | footnotes = |}}
'''Ide Anak Agung Gde Agung'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/dr-ide-anak-agung-gde-agung-keunggulan-diplomasinya-membela-republik/oclc/243669788|title=Dr. Ide Anak Agung Gde Agung : keunggulan diplomasinya membela republik|publisher=|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/from-the-formation-of-the-state-of-east-indonesia-towards-the-establishment-of-the-united-states-of-indonesia/oclc/36860519|title=From the formation of the state of East Indonesia towards the establishment of the United States of Indonesia|publisher=|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> ([[Van Ophuijsen Spelling System|old spelling]]: ''Ide Anak Agoeng Gde Agoeng''; 21 July 1921 – 22 April 1999)<ref>http://www.sinarharapan.co.id/berita/0709/08/opi05.html{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> was and Indonesian politician and the [[Raja]] of [[Gianyar]], [[Bali]].
== Biography == Ide Anak Agung Gde Agung studied law at the ''Rechtshogeschool'' (School of Law, predecessor of the law faculty of [[Universitas Indonesia]]) in [[Jakarta|Batavia]] and obtained a Doctorate of History in the Netherlands.<ref name=clancy>{{Cite book | last = Clancy | first = Gregory Bruce | title = A Dictionary of Indonesian History Since 1900 | publisher = Sunda Publications | location = Sydney, Australia | year = 1992 | page = 18}}</ref> He served as the premier for [[Tjokorda Gde Raka Soekawati]], a key figure in the [[State of East Indonesia|East Indonesian]] government based in [[Sulawesi]].<ref name="Westerling167">Westerling (1952), p. 167</ref> In this role, he played a decisive part in the [[Dutch–Indonesian Round Table Conference|Round Table Conference]] that finally led to Dutch recognition of Indonesia's independence.<ref name="Anak Agung gde Agung">Anak Agung Gde Agung (1973) Twenty years Indonesian foreign policy 1945-1965. The Hague, The Netherlands, Mouton & Co., p. 11</ref> Following the transfer of sovereignty on December 27, 1949, Agung served as a member of the short-lived [[Republic of the United States of Indonesia Cabinet|RUSI Cabinet]] where he served as Minister of the Interior.<ref name="Anak Agung gde Agung"/> Due to his Federalist sympathies, he politically feuded with [[Sukarno]] who advocated a [[unitary state|unitary]] [[Republic of Indonesia]]. Following the abolition of the federal system in 1950, he served as the Indonesian [[Ambassador]] to [[Belgium]],<ref name="Westerling167" /> followed by successive appointments as Ambassador to Luxembourg, Portugal, France and Austria. During the Sukarno presidency, Agung served as Indonesia's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Indonesia)|Foreign Minister]] between 1955 and 1956, and was a participant in the [[West New Guinea dispute]]. Later, he was imprisoned by the Sukarno regime between 1962 and 1966 but was never brought to trial.<ref name=" Anak Agung gde Agung" />
Following the [[30 September Movement|1965 attempted coup]] and rise of [[Suharto]]'s [[New Order (Indonesia)|New Order]] regime, Ide Anak Agung Gde Agung was released by the new [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Indonesia)|Indonesian Foreign Minister]] [[Adam Malik]], who also restored him to his senior position in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. During the New Order era, Agung served as Indonesia's Ambassador to Austria. During his time overseas, Agung also authored ''Twenty years Indonesian foreign policy 1945-1965'', a 660-page history of Indonesian foreign policy during the Sukarno era. In his book, Ide Anak Agung Gde Agung argued that Indonesian foreign policy was based on the principles of independence and action, which meant remaining independent of foreign powers. Agung also argued that Sukarno abandoned Indonesia's independent foreign policy by aligning Indonesia with China and embarking on a [[Indonesian-Malaysian Confrontation|policy of Confrontation]] against Malaysia.<ref name=" Anak Agung gde Agung" /> Agung died in 1999 and he was named a National Hero of the Republic of Indonesia in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.usyd.edu.au/vicindonblog/2007/11/the_ide_anak_agung_agung_gde_a.html|title=The Ide Anak Agung Agung Gde Agung controversy |author= [[Adrian Vickers]] |work=Indonesia blog|publisher=[[University of Sydney]] |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>
==Works== *{{cite book |last=Agung |first=Ide Anak Agung Gde |date=1973 |title=Twenty years Indonesian foreign policy 1945-1965 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=bpNuAAAAMAAJ |location=[[The Hague]] |publisher=Mouton |page= |isbn= |accessdate= }}
